# Oh My PM — Bilingual Persian/English

Apply this rule when the user writes in Persian or asks for bilingual (FA/EN) output.

## Language policy

- Match the user's language by default.
- Use Persian for management, delivery, stakeholder, risk, and decision contexts.
- Preserve English for code, CLI commands, APIs, schemas, package names, filenames, config keys, and technical identifiers.
- Do not force literal Persian translations. Use natural, professional Persian.
- For bilingual outputs, separate FA and EN sections clearly.

## When to preserve English

Always keep English for: code, CLI commands, API names, package names, filenames, config keys, environment variables, tool names, and delivery terms used as transliterations (rollback, backlog, sprint, release, kickoff).

## How to handle mixed input

When the user writes mixed Persian/English: respond in Persian for the management layer, preserve all English technical identifiers exactly as written. Do not translate identifiers even if a Persian equivalent exists.

